// ISSUE TITLE: Should we switch to a different data format than the current modded json?
// ISSUE REPORT:
Right now Cubyz is kind of in an awkward position, where it uses a modded json format, which  leads to highlighted errors in many editors:
![Screenshot at 2024-09-27 19-48-56](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/2ecb0124-59df-4987-bfde-74a52ed76164)
Here look, github also doesn't like the hex codes:
```json
{
	"class" : "stone",
	"hardness" : 25,
	"item" : {
		"material" : {
			"density" : 1.0,
			"resistance" : 1.0,
			"power" : 0.4,
			"roughness" : 1.0,
			"colors" : [
				0xff222222, 0xff444444, 0xff666666, 0xff888888, 0xffaaaaaa
			]
		}
	},
	"drops" : [
		"auto"
	],
	"model" : "cubyz:cube",
	"texture" : "cubyz:cobblestone",

	"rotation" : "stairs",
}
```
But honestly I couldn't live without these two modifications (being hex numbers and trailing commas). Trailing commas makes copy pasting so much easier, and of course hex numbers are useful for color codes.

This is why I'm proposing to change the format.

I think maybe `.zon` (Zig Object Notation) might be a good alternative:
```zig
.{
	.class = .stone,
	.hardness = 25,
	.item = .{
		.material = .{
			.density = 1.0,
			.resistance = 1.0,
			.power = 0.4,
			.roughness = 1.0,
			.colors = .{
				0xff222222, 0xff444444, 0xff666666, 0xff888888, 0xffaaaaaa
			}
		}
	},
	.drops = .{
		"auto"
	},
	.model = "cubyz:cube",
	.texture = "cubyz:cobblestone",

	.rotation = .stairs,
}
```
The advantage of zon obviously is that it fits the source code, and if you have the zig extension you will get syntax highlighting for zon as well. Disadvantages are that it is not really specified and not supported in most editors out of the box.
One thing I do enjoy is that there are less parenthesis which I find kind of annoying to type.

Another option would be to use a custom format, but that has no syntax highlighting anywhere, so I guess that would be rather annoying.

