// ISSUE TITLE: argparser allocator usage for the errorMessages is used inconsistently
// ISSUE REPORT:
The interface states that it should use the stackAllocator
```zig
/// `errorMessage` - out parameter used to store and return errors, if any occur. Has to be allocated with stackAllocator.
```
But most of the code actually uses the passed-in `allocator` for it which only happens to be the stack allocator (for now), and these errors are also hard to catch in a review.

I think the best solution would be to use a `List` instead of `ListUnmanaged`, so there is no chance to use the wrong allocator. The reason for using the unmanaged list is #1181.

This issue should not block the migration effort that has already started.

// DISCUSSION:
[MAINTAINER COMMENT]
I just want to mention that this issue would not exist is we were to use Result struct instead of out parameter.

[MAINTAINER COMMENT]
But Result struct would require needlessly allocating and copying the error strings around all the time right?

[MAINTAINER COMMENT]
Would it? We could still use current approach internally, just return an Result object from the public function. I need to try to implement that to check.

[MAINTAINER COMMENT]
What about the parse function of custom structs though?

[MAINTAINER COMMENT]
Nothing, it gets pre-allocated list object and an appropriate allocator, so problem doesn't exist.
Problem exists only upon list creation.

[MAINTAINER COMMENT]
I think this can wait until after #3073 and after the usages of the ArgParser helper are consilidated outside the command to reduce the number of changes needed.

[MAINTAINER COMMENT]
Yes, many of the command PRs had this problem. I decided to not worry about it in reviews to allow us to progress faster, after #3073 it should be easier to resolve all the incorrect use cases.

[MAINTAINER COMMENT]
IMO we should just use `allocator` everywhere, as it clearly makes impression that it should be used. Additionally we have this very bad pattern of interleaving allocations from different scopes using `stackAllocator`. From perspective of `parse` using `stackAllocator` for `errorMessage` looks like explicitly using `stackAllocator` for resource that outlives the scope where `stackAllocator` is used.
That is a clear contradiction with our guidelines:

> - local lifetime, things that are freed at the end of the scope (including local data structures such as lists) → `main.stackAllocator`

It would be much more standard and much easier to explain 

> "errorMessage has same lifetime as Args and use same allocator"

which is *the default way unmanaged code works*. Allocator is runtime concern, not part of the types. Main reason why this issue even exist is that we insisted on explicitly using `stackAllocator` in a way intertwined with `errorMessage` param.

```zig
			var tempErrorMessage: ListUnmanaged(u8) = .{};
			defer tempErrorMessage.deinit(main.stackAllocator);

			var nextArgument: ?[]const u8 = tokens.next();

			inline for (s.fields) |field| {
				const value = resolveArgument(field.type, allocator, field.name[0..], nextArgument, &tempErrorMessage);

				if (value == error.ParseError) {
					if (@typeInfo(field.type) == .optional) {
						@field(result, field.name) = null;
						tempErrorMessage.clearRetainingCapacity();
					} else {
						errorMessage.appendSlice(main.stackAllocator, tempErrorMessage.items);
						return error.ParseError;
					}
				} else {
					@field(result, field.name) = value catch unreachable;
					tempErrorMessage.clearRetainingCapacity();
					nextArgument = tokens.next();
				}
			}
```

We could have just added comment why this is an exception from the rule, rather than making the exception everywhere we use `errorMessages` now.

I do still agree that `errorMessages` having a precondition of being allocated with `allocator` is weird and bug prone, but we don't have to violate zig style approach of not using managed data structures, if we just return dedicated error object with typical lifetime rule of "you own it, please defer deinit()".

[MAINTAINER COMMENT]
I think it's not worth discussing this further. For now we should go with a simple solution, whether that is making an exception or using managed lists is not really relevant.
#3132 might require a bit of a change of paradigms here anyways, particularly with errors from skipped optionals.

